Text.Value: I should gather my strength. I've waited so long for this, a little longer won't do any harm...
Still, I am... unused to it. I can only hope she forgives a slip of the tongue now and again, until I adapt.
Yes. Now you know all that is worth knowing. Let us put this behind us, for good.
Well it depends - do you find yourself more hirsute at certain times, craving warm flesh? Actually no - spare your father the answer to that.
Very well... but I shall not wallow in ugly details. That is what they would have wanted - to have let their physical torments live on in our spirits. I will not allow that.

EditorData.NodeContext: Conceding, but on his non-negotiable terms,

Text.Value: Shadowheart, my darling. All is well, I hope.
I had promised you we would catch up once I'd rested - perhaps there's something you wish to ask about.
You must not blame yourself. You were a child; your mother and I were supposed to protect you.
I'm starting to feel like my old self again. And Jen - I mean Shadowheart - has been able to unbottle some of the feelings that Shar denied to her.
You are more than just a friend to her, aren't you? I saw the way she looked at you. It reminded me of her mother, when we first met.
What happened during all those years? What did they make your daughter do to you?
We grew complacent - underestimated the depths of Shar's bitterness, the fanaticism of her followers.
We were still a family, in that room. Suffering. Enduring. But we did not give up. Your mother and I swore we would see the look of recognition in your eyes once again. And we did.

Knowing you were out there still was enough to sustain us. And you are stronger than us both, daughter. We merely had to endure - you had to choose your path. One that brought you back to us, at last.
You've shown great kindness, allowing my wife and I to remain with you. Thank you. I'm glad Jenevelle found you.
But when I found you, you did not see your father, rushing to save you - you only saw a wolf, hunting you in the darkness.
How is your wife - Emmeline?
Perhaps... perhaps later, my girl. That is a hard thing to talk about. I fear I do not have the strength for it just yet.
They made me do things to you both, all those years. Please - I need to know.
How did you both go on like that? I could never have the strength...
You accept your daughter's choice of name?
Perhaps they did - ours was a small community, spread thin.
What comes next for you?
Why did nobody else help you? Or come to search for us?
Both. They marked you before our eyes. They said it would discipline you for straying, while extending our torment also.
Don't worry - I am truly glad she found you, and I have scant energy to play the stern father.
And Shadowheart too may wish to join us perhaps, once she's helped you put down this 'Absolute' threat.
You could have done nothing back then - not without putting yourself in danger. The Moonmaiden guided you in her own time.
But do not worry. We're together again - and we will make every moment count all the more.
All these years... you were so close by. And I did nothing.
Some rest, perhaps, will make me better company.
And Shadowheart too may wish to join us perhaps, with her fine paramour at her side - once you've put down this 'Absolute' threat together.
Whatever we have left, I must make count for double - triple. But later, perhaps. I still need time to recover my strength.
My wife will need care. I wish to find somewhere quiet, close to nature. Where the sun can warm us, and the moon can watch over us as we sleep.
When I awakened, you were gone, but your mother was with me. They were spiriting us away to the city, hidden and bound.
Whatever Jenevelle wishes of us. She still has other fights. But when she's ready, we'll be there. To be a family again.
How is mother coping?
If you're a lycanthrope, does that mean I am also?
I'm sorry. This would never have happened if I hadn't been frightened, if I hadn't ran.
Instead, the Sharrans used us to teach you different lessons. Painful lessons.
What about the wound on my hand? Was that to hurt me, or you?
So you're a lycanthrope? Shadowheart shared some of her memories with me.
I'm sorry.
We will talk again soon, my sweet. Once I've had some time to gather myself.
She is strong... but she is also human. The years were harder on her than on me, in both body and mind. Shar's pit robbed us of precious time we can never have back.
Are you sure, Shadowheart...? Picking at old wounds may not serve any purpose...

EditorData.NodeContext: Reluctant. Wants to shield his daughter.

Text.Value: Don't be. Knowing you were out there gave us the strength to hold on. And you returned to us, just like you were supposed to, all that time ago.
I've heard enough about this 'Absolute' threat to understand it cannot be ignored. Your mother and I can wait until you prevail - and I know you will.
They made me do things to you both, all those years. Please - I need to know.
I took on my wolf-form to cover the ground more quickly. And it worked - I followed your scent, and reached you before the Sharrans could.
Please. I need to understand, if I'm to move on.
She is strong... but she is also human. The years were harder on her than on me, in both body and mind. Shar's pit robbed us of precious time we can never have back.
There's so much I want to ask about.
The failing was mine.
What really happened that night in the woods, when I was abducted?
How is it you could transform into a wolf at will?
What comes now?
They had you use us for... practice. All the techniques that the Sharrans hold pride in. Trickery, interrogation... torture. They even had you, our own daughter, try to convert us.

EditorData.NodeContext: Difficult for him. Decades of painful memories touched upon in a couple of phrases.

Text.Value: What comes next for us?
Jen - I mean, Shadowheart, pardon. It warms my heart to see you.

EditorData.NodeContext: Accidentally using Shadowheart's birth name (slip of the tongue) before correcting himself

Text.Value: You panicked, and before I could explain, the Sharrans found us. Father and daughter. Wolf and prey.
Leave.
Leave.
Somewhere quiet, close to nature. Where the sun can warm us, and the moon can watch over us as we sleep.
They took us both.
As am I.
I can only imagine. It may take a little time before I'm fit to give many answers though. Forty years in captivity have left my mind... cobwebbed. But it will clear, given some rest.
That name - I'm still not used to hearing it.
Jenevelle. I still can't believe you freed us - that I'm standing here with you. I'd ask you to slap me so I know it's real, but I don't think I'm yet strong enough to bear it.
That name. I don't know how I feel about it.
That should have been the day you came of age, and into the Moonmaiden's teachings.
Selne's blessings to you.
You have your mother's wisdom. Yes. I should gather my strength. I've waited so long for this, a little longer won't do any harm...
You promised you'd tell me what I did to you both. I'm ready to hear it now.
Nor is Jenevelle. Perhaps that is something I shall need to talk to her about, when the time is right.
The Moonmaiden's blessings are many. She taught me to control the curse - but she could not teach me to control my paternal instincts.
A great deal of damage was done to our family, but we can still heal.
But perhaps this was always meant to be. Perhaps the Moonmaiden's path was merely longer for you than we knew.
You should rest. There'll be time to talk later.
I've gleaned enough from word around this camp to know you're more than capable. You will prevail.
The worst part was not anything you did to us - it is what they had done to you. You didn't recognise us. Those eyes I had wiped tears from now looked at me like a stranger.
I... I feared I would give in then, but your mother's strength bolstered me. She never gave up calling you daughter, no matter what you said. Or did.
If you have not changed after all this time, I believe you are safe.
Beyond that, your mother will need my care - and yours too, if you wish to join us.
There must be stories you could tell... but perhaps another time.
Of course. Only a fool would alienate his child over a name. Shadowheart must determine her own path - that is what the Moonmaiden teaches.
Give it time. Give us time. This is a great deal to take on at once - for me as well.
I'm sorry, but what happened in that room... it must stay within the family. Just know that we endured, and are grateful for your help.

EditorData.NodeContext: Firmly but politely shutting down the question

Text.Value: I should have told you of my curse before that night. Then... everything would have been different.
I've heard enough.
I had to find you - to bring you home - and I had to do it quickly. In my haste, I made a terrible mistake.
What happened during all those years? What did they make your daughter do to you?
Forgive me, I am still weak - aching limbs, fogged mind. I'll prove better company after I've rested, I assure you.
But you were not alone in the woods. We caught a Sharran spy near our village, and learned that his accomplices sought to abduct you.
You're not upset, are you? About my name?
Not just with the pain, but with the knowledge that every time we felt it, your true self was being punished, for trying to break through their indoctrination.
You were to come of age that night - left alone in the woods, and using only Selne's guidance to find your way back to us.
There is nothing old about these wounds - they've never been allowed to heal. I would know.
Unfortunately I was unable to stop what befell us, as neither elf nor wolf.
A name is nothing. Your happiness is what matters. Just... forgive your father the occasional slip of the tongue. I will adapt, given time.
I am a lycanthrope, but your mother is not. It was a toss of the coin to determine if you inherited that side of me.
I am, but with Selne's guidance, I learned how to control the beast long ago - I only let it loose again when my family was threatened.
I'm afraid my strength has not returned just yet. Decades in that place has left me maimed, body and soul.

Synopsis:
Default camp dialog for Shadowheart's dad. He has started to  recover from her ordeal in the Shar grotto.
He has unique branches for Shadowheart and non-Shadowheart players, as well as branches that occur before and after CAMP_Shadowheart_DaughterTears, in which SH and her parents have their first proper heart to heart following their reunion.
